The line of intersection of the planes $x + y + z - 6 = 0$ and $2x + 3y + 4z + 5 = 0$ is perpendicular to both of the normals of the planes.  First, we look at the normals of each plane: \[(1,1,1) \text{ and } (2,3,4).\]We can find the direction vector for the line $L$ using the cross product: \[\begin{vmatrix}
\mathbf{i} & \mathbf{j} & \mathbf{k}\\ 1 & 1 & 1\\ 2 & 3 & 4
\end{vmatrix}\]We can expand this 3x3 determinant along the top row to get \[\mathbf{i}\begin{vmatrix} 1 & 1 \\ 3 & 4 \end{vmatrix} - \mathbf{j}\begin{vmatrix} 1 & 1 \\ 2 & 4 \end{vmatrix} + \mathbf{k}\begin{vmatrix} 1 & 1 \\ 2 & 3 \end{vmatrix}.\]We know how to find a 2x2 determinant! Using the formula $(ad - bc),$ we have three 2x2 determinants to evaluate: \begin{align*} \mathbf{i}\begin{vmatrix} 1 & 1 \\ 3 & 4 \end{vmatrix} &= \mathbf{i}((1)(4) - (3)(1)) = \mathbf{i}(1) = \mathbf{i},\\ - \mathbf{j}\begin{vmatrix} 1 & 1 \\ 2 & 4 \end{vmatrix} &= -\mathbf{j}((1)(4) - (2)(1)) = - \mathbf{j}(2) = - 2\mathbf{j},\\ + \mathbf{k}\begin{vmatrix} 1 & 1 \\ 2 & 3 \end{vmatrix} &= \mathbf{k}((1)(3) - (2)(1)) = \mathbf{k}(1) = \mathbf{k}.\end{align*} Putting these three vectors together, we get the direction vector $\boxed{(1,-2,1)}$ for the line $L.$</think> <answer>The plane orthogonal to the line $L$ and going through the point $(1,1,1)$ is given by the solution set of \[(1,-2,1) \cdot (x - 1, y - 1, z - 1) = 0.\]We already expanded the inner products! Plugging in the direction vector we found, we have \[\mathbf{i}(x-1) - \mathbf{j}(2(y-1)) + \mathbf{k}(z-1) = 0.\]Using the definition of the dot product, we can rewrite this in the form $Ax + By + Cz + D$ and put any negative coefficients $A,$ $B,$ or $C$ into $A$ with $A > 0$ to get \[1(x - 1) - 2(y -1) + 1(z -1) = 0,\]or $\boxed{x - 2y + z = 0}.$</answer>
